1 Differential expression

1.1 Differential expression using limma-voom and SVA

Differential expression analysis consists of identifying changes in gene expression. For RNAseq experiments, this means comparing relative concentrations of RNA molecules. In R, this can be done by using the limma and sva R/Bioconductor packages.

1.1.0.1 Analysis

limma allows for linear model analysis of data for DE. This requires building two model matrices: a matrix of the model including the outcome of interest and adjustment variables, and a matrix of the null model that only includes adjustment variables. The outcome of interest is the type of sample (tumor vs normal), and as both types of samples come from the same patient the analysis is paired, so a unique identifier for each patient is included. Finally, as there are unknown factors to adjust, an intercept term of 1 is given to the null model.

Even if no known sources of variation were found, surrogate variables representing unknown sources of variation can be added to the model. Those can be estimated with the sva package, and later be appended to the model. Finally, voom is used to fit the model as the library size distribution is not uniform across samples, and the moderated t-statistics are calculated.

library(sva)
# Obtain the patient ID, as the analysis is paired
patientid <- substr(colnames(se.filt), 9, 12)
samplevial <- substr(colnames(se.filt), 14, 16)

# Build the model (mod) and null (mod0) matrices 
mod <- model.matrix(~type + patientid, data = colData(se.filt))
mod0 <- model.matrix(~1, data = colData(se.filt))

# Estimate surrogate variables
sv <- sva(assays(se.filt)$logCPM, mod = mod, mod0 = mod0)
Number of significant surrogate variables is:  12 
Iteration (out of 5 ):1  2  3  4  5  
#pv <- f.pvalue(assays(se.filt)$logCPM, mod, mod0)
#sum(p.adjust(pv, method="fdr") < 0.01)

# Add surrogates to the design matrix
len <- length(colnames(mod))
mod <- cbind(mod, sv$sv)
colnames(mod) <- c(colnames(mod)[1:len], paste0("SV", 1:sv$n))
v <- voom(dge.filt, mod, plot=TRUE)

Figure 1: Mean-variance plot for DE analysis with SVA

fit <- lmFit(v, mod) # Fit the model with the voom weights
fit <- eBayes(fit) # Calculate moderated t-statistics

sva was able to estimate 12 surrogate variables. Regarding the mean-variance plot shown in Figure 1, which was obtained with voom, it shows the variance in the y axis and the mean of expression in the x axis for each gene, represented as a black dot. Such plots contain a red curve that is fitted to the dots and show trends in the data. Normally increases in expression levels mean a decrease in the variance, until a plateau is reached for highly expressed genes. This trend is observed in the plot obtained for this data. Moreover, the plot is also a diagnosis of filtering steps performed upstream. The fact that there is not a drop in variance for the lower expression values indicates that the filtering threshold was good.

As we are performing multiple tests, the probability of type I errors (rejecting the null hypotheses when it is true) increases. There are multiple statistical strategies to decrease the likelihood of these errors, such as the false discovery rate (FDR). This technique consists of defining an acceptable rate of type I errors (false discoveries). Here, a FDR of 0.1 is set, which means that 10% of the rejections of the null hypothesis will be incorrect. For example, if the data set has 11872 observations, up to 1187 genes can be false positives (FP).

FDRcutoff <- 0.1
res <- decideTests(fit, p.value = FDRcutoff)
summary(res)

1.1.0.2 Diagnostics

The distribution of raw p-values and the QQ plot moderated t-statistics, displayed in Figure 2, can be used as a diagnosis of the tests performed.

par(mfrow = c(1, 2), mar = c(4, 5, 2, 2))
hist(tt$P.Value, xlab = "Raw P-values", main = "", las = 1)
qqt(fit$t[, 2], df = fit$df.prior + fit$df.residual, main = "", pch = ".", cex = 3)
abline(0, 1, lwd = 2)

Figure 2: Raw p-values distribution and QQ plot of the moderated t-statistics for DE analysis with SVA

Under the null hypothesis, which is that most genes are not differentially expressed, the raw p-value distribution should be uniform with a peak at low p-values for the truly DE genes. It is not the case.

Regarding the QQ plot, it represents the quantiles of our data sample against the theoretical distribution they should follow. The diagonal represents the null hypothesis. Most genes are off-diagonal, indicating that differentially expressed genes exist, but they are still close to the diagonal because they are not significant.

1.2 Alternative differential expression analysis approaches

As said previously, adding surrogate variables adjusts for unknown variation, which in practice would translate into an increased number of differentially expressed genes with respect to analyses performed without including them. Usually this unknown variation would account for non-biological variability, but in some cases the surrogate variables can capture biological variability that is important for the outcome. One of such cases happens when there is some sort of heterogeneity in the data, such as unknown subgroups. When this happens, sva is not reccomended.

Following this idea, two different modifications to the surrogate variables before performing the diferential expression analysis were done. In the first case they were not included, while only one of them was removed in the second. Note that code that was identical to the first analysis will not be displayed for clarity.

1.2.1 Differential expression analysis without surrogate variable adjustment

The first analysis will consist on the removal of the surrogate variable estimation and inclusion into the model.

# Obtain the patient ID, as the analysis is paired
patientid <- substr(colnames(se.filt), 9, 12)
samplevial <- substr(colnames(se.filt), 14, 16)

# Build the model (mod) and null (mod0) matrices 
mod <- model.matrix(~type + patientid, data = colData(se.filt))
mod0 <- model.matrix(~1, data = colData(se.filt))

v <- voom(dge.filt, mod, plot=TRUE)

Figure 3: Mean-variance plot for DE analysis without SVA

fit <- lmFit(v, mod) # Fit the model with the voom weights
fit <- eBayes(fit) # Calculate moderated t-statistics

sva was able to estimate 12 surrogate variables. There are not relevant variations in the mean-variance plot, shown in Figure 3

The correction for multiple testing is the same as in the previous analysis, a FDR of 0.01. After this, gene metadata is added for interpretation purposes.

1.2.1.1 Diagnostics

The performance of the statistical test is assessed in the 5 with the distribution of raw p-values and the QQ plot moderated t-statistics.

Figure 5: Raw p-values distribution and QQ plot of the moderated t-statistics for DE analysis without SVA

The assumption of a flat distribution of raw p-values for the non-DE genes under the null hypothesis holds in this case. In the QQ plot, more genes are far from the null hypothesis, which indicates significant differential expression.

The results are diagnosed with volcano and MA plots, in which the top 10 differentially expressed genes are highlighted as shown in Figure 6. 

par(mfrow = c(1, 2), mar = c(4, 5, 3, 2))
volcanoplot(fit, coef = 2, highlight = 10, names = fit$genes$symbol, main = "Volcano Plot")

limma::plotMA(fit, coef = 2, status = rownames(fit$lods) %in% DEgenes, legend = FALSE,
main = "MA Plot", hl.pch = 46, hl.cex = 4, bg.pch = 46, bg.cex = 3, las = 1)
text(fit$Amean[top], fit$coef[top, 2], fit$genes$symbol[top], cex = 0.5, pos = 4)

1.2.2 Differential expression analysis removing the first surrogate variable

The removal of all the surrogate variables might be considered radical, as some of them might be capturing part of the unwanted non-biological variation. It is possible that only one of the variables is capturing the relevant biological information. By removing each of them one at a time, it was observed that the variable responsible for this was the first one, so the following analysis is performed by removing it. The others can be done by simply modifying the number on the svmod <- sv$sv[,-1] line.

1.2.2.1 Analysis

library(sva)
# Obtain the patient ID, as the analysis is paired
patientid <- substr(colnames(se.filt), 9, 12)
samplevial <- substr(colnames(se.filt), 14, 16)

# Build the model (mod) and null (mod0) matrices 
mod <- model.matrix(~type + patientid, data = colData(se.filt))
mod0 <- model.matrix(~1, data = colData(se.filt))

# Estimate surrogate variables
sv <- sva(assays(se.filt)$logCPM, mod = mod, mod0 = mod0)
Number of significant surrogate variables is:  12 
Iteration (out of 5 ):1  2  3  4  5  
# Remove the first surrogate variable
svmod <- sv$sv[,-1]

# Add surrogates to the design matrix
len <- length(colnames(mod))
mod <- cbind(mod, svmod)
colnames(mod) <- c(colnames(mod)[1:len], paste0("SV", 1:(sv$n-1)))
v <- voom(dge.filt, mod, plot=TRUE)

Figure 7: Mean-variance plot for DE analysis without SV1

fit <- lmFit(v, mod) # Fit the model with the voom weights
fit <- eBayes(fit) # Calculate moderated t-statistics

sva estimated 12 surrogate variables, though 11 will be used. There are not relevant variations in the mean-variance plot (Figure 7)

The correction for multiple testing is maintained to a FDR of 0.01. Some preliminary data on upregulation and downregulation is obtained and gene metadata is added for interpretation purposes.

1.2.2.2 Diagnostics

The performance of the statistical test is diagnosed with the distributions of raw p-values and moderated t-statistics, as shown in Figure 9.

Figure 9: Raw p-values distribution and QQ plot of the moderated t-statistics for DE analysis without SV1

The result is, again, similar to the previous analysis. The flat distribution for non-DE genes is present, but the peak is higher, as there are more differentially expressed genes. The QQ plot is similar to the in the analysis without SVA.

The results are diagnosed with volcano and MA plots, in which the top 10 differentially expressed genes are highlighted, shown in Figure @ref{fig:volcanoplot-noSV1}.
